
### Opening files

```bash
for dict in dict1.pdf dict2.pdf dict3.pdf;
do start $dict;
done
```

Save the script as `your_script_name.sh` and call it from the shell with `bash your_script_name.sh`



-   [https://explainshell.com/](https://explainshell.com/)
-   ![](data:image/png;base64,)
-   cd - to swtich back to the past working directory
-   wc to get line count, word count, and character count
-   | to pipe chain commands
-   Using [find and grep](https://swcarpentry.github.io/shell-novice/07-find/index.html)
-   Use sed "s\current\replace\g" to do replacement either for file names or for content in files, used -I argument in sed to actually do the replacement (otherwise you just show the change without making the change)
-   ![](data:image/png;base64,)
-   ^for matching a space in the first slash
-   seq 10 to print out 1:10
-   Also {1..3..10} or {a..e}
-   [paste](https://datascienceatthecommandline.com/2e/list-of-command-line-tools.html#paste) things together like 1+2+3+4+5+6 using seq 6 | paste -sd+
-   diff file1 file2 to see what is different between them

-   read to take user input
-   echo $? gives the exit status of the last thing you ran

-   [xargs](https://www.tecmint.com/xargs-command-examples/) reads streams of data from standard input, then generates and executes command lines; meaning it can take output of a command and passes it as argument of another command.
-   [xargs](https://www.howtoforge.com/tutorial/linux-xargs-command/) to search for multiple file extensions simultaneously (e.g. .txt and .csv and .pdf)
